n","print(len(s))\n","print(s[0])\n","print(s[-3:-1])"],"metadata":{"colab":{"base_uri":"https://localhost:8080/"},"id":"GQl6Z3idXwz4","executionInfo":{"status":"ok","timestamp":1770373929483,"user_tz":-330,"elapsed":30,"user":{"displayName":"Ishan Mitra","userId":"17835533516491823062"}},"outputId":"43c063ce-5cd6-4bb7-87cc-f6abca8934dc"},"execution_count":null,"outputs":[{"output_type":"stream","name":"stdout","text":["27\n","d\n","el\n"]}]},{"cell_type":"code","source":["# Deleting the user-defined variable 'str' to restore the built-in str() function\n","del str\n","\n","# Now, re-running the original code that caused the error\n","a1=1234\n","# Convert the integer to a string before using isdigit()\n","print(str(a1).isdigit())"],"metadata":{"id":"z9BPWJvOXw3L","colab":{"base_uri":"https://localhost:8080/"},"executionInfo":{"status":"ok","timestamp":1770977714612,"user_tz":-330,"elapsed":10,"user":{"displayName":"Ishan Mitra","userId":"17835533516491823062"}},"outputId":"bf4d1570-5452-43dc-9ebe-366483c9a901"},"execution_count":null,"outputs":[{"output_type":"stream","name":"stdout","text":["True\n"]}]},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":["# Assignment On Date- 06/02/2026.\n"," **100 lines of coding**\n","-why python contain trash bin\n","-what is two step compilation"],"metadata":{"id":"S4H0lPGQJGJo"}},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":["# **Why Python has a “trash bin” (Garbage Collection)?**\n","\n","When you create **variables, objects, lists**, etc., Python stores them in memory.\n","After you stop using them, Python needs to remove them to free memory. Otherwise, the program would consume too much RAM and slow down.\n","How Python Garbage Collection Works\n","\n","**Reference Counting**\n","\n","Python counts how many references (links) point to an object.\n","\n","When the reference count becomes zero, the object is deleted.\n"],"metadata":{"id":"75tsw7nSOTWJ"}},{"cell_type":"code","source":["a = [1, 2, 3]\n","b = a\n","print(a, b) # Printing 'a' and 'b' before they are deleted.\n","del a\n","del b"],"metadata":{"colab":{"base_uri":"https://localhost:8080/"},"id":"ob5Vw3sVNb3B","executionInfo":{"status":"ok","timestamp":1770889443717,"user_tz":-330,"elapsed":34,"user":{"displayName":"Ishan Mitra","userId":"17835533516491823062"}},"outputId":"61faed9c-3c48-4518-f215-2c4da9a91af1"},"execution_count":null,"outputs":[{"output_type":"stream","name":"stdout","text":["[1, 2, 3] [1, 2, 3]\n"]}]},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":["# **Cycle** **Detection**\n","\n","Sometimes objects refer to each other (circular references).\n","\n","Reference counting alone cannot remove them.\n","\n","Python uses a special Garbage Collector to detect and delete them.\n","Why It Is Important\n","\n","Saves memory automatically\n","\n","Prevents memory leaks\n","\n","Makes programming easier **(no manual memory deletion like C/C++)**\n","]\n","**Simple Real-Life Example**\n","\n","Think of Python memory like your room:\n","\n","Objects = Items in your room\n","\n","Garbage collector = Person who throws unused items in trash\n","\n","Keeps room clean and organized\n"],"metadata":{"id":"snzVEwJgOwER"}},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":["# **what is two step compilation?**\n","\n","Two step compilation is the process where a program is converted into machine-executable code in two separate stages instead of directly running the source code.\n","\n","**Step 1: Compilation**\n","\n","The compiler converts the source code (written in high-level language like C, C++, etc.) into object code.\n","\n","The object code is not directly executable.\n","\n","It checks syntax errors and translates code into low-level instructions.\n","\n","Example\n","\n","***`Source Code → Object Code`***\n","\n","**Step 2: Linking**\n","\n","The linker combines object code with required libraries and other files.\n","\n","It produces the final executable file (.exe, .out, etc.).\n","\n","Example\n","\n","***`Object Code + Libraries → Executable Program`***\n","\n","***`Source Code → Compiler → Object Code → Linker → Executable File`***\n","Why Two Step Compilation Is Used\n","\n","Helps detect errors early\n","\n","Allows use of external libraries\n","\n","Makes large program development easier\n","\n","Improves program modularity\n","\n","\n","Example (C Language)\n","gcc program.c   (Compilation + Linking happens internally)\n","\n","\n","Internally:\n","\n","program.c → program.o (Compilation)\n","\n","program.o → program.exe (Linking)\n"],"metadata":{"id":"M8QP1NYuREPl"}},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":["# Assignment On Date- 09/02/2026 and 11/02/2026\n","\n","Explain input () function with  an example\n","Programme - to find largest of three numbers\n","Explain formatted output with print() Arithmetic operators\n"," Operator precedence In python\n"," Difference between == and is\n","Difference between relational and logical operators\n"," Programme to check a no is odd or even\n","Check whether no lies between two values\n"," What are command assignment operator"],"metadata":{"id":"GKQZwR53yEG2"}},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":["# **1. input() Function in Python**\n","\n","Definition\n","\n","The input() function is used to take data from the user during program execution.\n","It always returns the input as a string.\n","\n","Syntax\n","\n","`variable = input(\"Message\")`\n","\n","Example\n","\n","`name = input(\"Enter your name: \")\n","print(\"Hello\", name)`\n","\n","\n","\n","If you want numbers, you must convert using int() or float().\n","\n","Example:\n","\n","`num = int(input(\"Enter a number: \"))`\n","\n","`print(num)`"],"metadata":{"id":"8KpgZ-NQzINV"}},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":["# Formatted Output using print()\n","🔹 Definition\n","\n","Formatted output means printing values in a proper and readable format.\n","\n","🔹 Methods\n","✔ Using f-string (Most Common)\n","name = \"Ishan\"\n","age = 23\n","print(f\"My name is {name} and I am {age} years old\")\n","\n","✔ Using format()\n","print(\"My name is {} and age is {}\".format(name, age))\n","\n","✔ Using % Operator\n","print(\"Age is %d\" % age)\n","\n","# Arithmetic Operators in Python\n","Operator\tMeaning\tExample\n","+\tAddition\t5 + 2 = 7\n","-\tSubtraction\t5 - 2 = 3\n","*\tMultiplication\t5 * 2 = 10\n","/\tDivision\t5 / 2 = 2.5\n","%\tModulus (remainder)\t5 % 2 = 1\n","//\tFloor division\t5 // 2 = 2\n","**\tExponent\t5 ** 2 = 25\n","# Operator Precedence in Python\n","\n","Operator precedence decides which operation is performed first.\n","\n","🔹 Order (High → Low)\n","\n","() Parentheses\n","\n","** Exponent\n","\n","* / // %\n","\n","+ -\n","\n","Comparison operators\n","\n","Logical operators\n","\n","🔹 Example\n","result = 5 + 2 * 3\n","print(result)\n","\n","\n","👉 Output = 11\n","(Because multiplication happens first)\n","\n","# Difference Between == and is\n","==\tis\n","Checks value equality\tChecks memory location\n","Used to compare values\tUsed to compare objects\n","🔹 Example\n","a = [1,2]\n","b = [1,2]\n","\n","print(a == b)   # True\n","print(a is b)   # False\n","\n","# Difference Between Relational and Logical Operators\n","🔹 Relational Operators\n","\n","Used to compare two values.\n","\n","Examples:\n","\n",">, <, >=, <=, ==, !=\n","\n","\n","Example:\n","\n","5 > 3   # True\n","\n","🔹 Logical Operators\n","\n","Used to combine conditions.\n","\n","Examples:\n","\n","and, or, not\n","\n","\n","Example:\n","\n","(5 > 3) and (4 > 2)"],"metadata":{"id":"P1gRzcRjzIYD"}},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":[],"metadata":{"id":"np7EaEWxzIbB"}},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":[],"metadata":{"id":"4U67s5x_zId9"}},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":[],"metadata":{"id":"TtkJoZZbzIg6"}},{"cell_type":"code","source":["a = int(input(\"Enter first number: \"))\n","b = int(input(\"Enter second number: \"))\n","c = int(input(\"Enter third number: \"))\n","\n","if a > b and a > c:\n","    print(\"Largest number is\", a)\n","elif b > c:\n","    print(\"Largest number is\", b)\n","else:\n","    print(\"Largest numbe